<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-dim-analysis-uncertainties-afr" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Applications and Further Reading</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Every chapter in this book has an applications and further reading section.
      The applications section is meant to give you a taste of how phenomena described in a chapter appear in the real world.
      They are to be read as bullet points, and you can pick and choose which ones to read.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-dim-analysis-uncertainties-applications">
    <title>Applications</title>

    <p>
      While Dave and his team were worried about a 500 kg statue, real-world scientists worry about the stability of the SI units across centuries.
      The <term>Global Positioning System (GPS)</term> relies on the definition of the second using the Cesium hyperfine transition frequency.
      Indeed, if a satellite was inaccurate by just a few nanoseconds, it would lead to errors of several meters in the GPS system.
    </p>

    <p>
      GPS systems also account for a significant systematic error arising from general relativity.
      Gravity causes time to run slower, so the clocks on the GPS satellites (which are further from Earth's center of mass) run faster than those on the ground.
      If this effect were not accounted for, the GPS system would accumulate errors, causing a catastrophic failure of the system.
    </p>

    <p>
      Trading firms use atomic clocks to time their trades to the nanosecond.
      If two firms' clocks are out of sync by even a millisecond, it can lead to massive systematic errors in market pricing and regulatory chaos.
      Time literally is money.
    </p>

    <p>
      Situation in which information is limited are ubiquitous in forensic science.
      Investigators use Fermi estimation techniques to make educated guesses about crime scenes.
      By estimating the volume of blood found and the rate of cooling, for instance, a forensic scientist can estimate the time of death of a victim.
    </p>

    <p>
      In 1707, the British fleet hit the rocks of the Scilly Isles, killing 2,000 sailors.
      The cause? A systematic error in timekeeping.
      Before GPS, longitude was calculated by comparing local time to a reference clock.
      A clock that was precise but not accurate (losing a few seconds a day) resulted in a position error of many miles <mdash /> the same "shaky hand" measurement error Sarah made, but with warships instead of statues.
    </p>

    <p>
      The most famous Fermi problem is the Fermi Paradox, which asks why we haven't found any evidence of extraterrestrial life given the vastness of the universe.
      Through a series of logical steps and estimates <mdash /> just as we did <mdash /> Fermi estimated that there should be many advanced civilizations in our galaxy, yet we haven't found any evidence of them.
    </p>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-dim-analysis-uncertainties-further-reading">
    <title>Further Reading</title>

    <p>
      You might be interested in learning more about the SI units and the history of their definitions.
      For that, check out the <em>SI Brochure</em>, published by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) <xref ref="ref-si-brochure"/>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Fermi problems are a fun way to practice estimation and dimensional analysis.
      The University of Maryland has a great collection of Fermi problems, which you can find in <xref ref="ref-umd-fermi"/>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
